          "settings": {
            "title": "What causes mouth sores?",
            "content": "Experts are split on the exact cause of mouth sores, but many believe their frequency depends on genetics, or hereditary factors. Regardless, other circumstances like hormonal fluctuations, stress, food allergies, vitamin deficiencies, or even the vigorous over-brushing of teeth can contribute to their development."
          }
        },
        "accordion_item_MGT7x3": {
          "type": "accordion_item",
          "settings": {
            "title": "How long do mouth sores last?",
            "content": "Usually, mouth sores heal after a week or two. More significant growths, called major mouth sores, may stick around for up to six weeks and possibly leave oral scarring"
          }
        },
        "accordion_item_zeQ9LJ": {
          "type": "accordion_item",
          "settings": {
            "title": "How do you get rid of mouth sores?",
            "content": "There is no cure-all for canker sores, but you can relieve your pain and quicken the healing process with a combination of treatments, which may include a mouthwash, a pain-relieving ointment, a prescription medication, supplements, and/or a medical procedure."
          }
        },
