          "settings": {
            "title": "What causes canker sores?",
            "content": "<p>The term “canker sore” is <a href=\"https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/diseases/21766-mouth-ulcer\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" onclick=\"javascript:window.open('https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/diseases/21766-mouth-ulcer', '_blank', 'noopener'); return false;\" data-uw-rm-brl=\"PR\" data-uw-original-href=\"https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/diseases/21766-mouth-ulcer\">interchangeable</a> with “mouth ulcer.” These painful sores can be caused by a variety of factors including genetics, hormonal fluctuations, vitamin deficiencies, food allergies, and oral irritation, among others. Interestingly, research also shows that canker sores are <a href=\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8934078/#ref3:~:text=women%20are%20at%20a%20slightly%20greater%20risk%20than%20men\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" onclick=\"javascript:window.open('https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8934078/#ref3:~:text=women%20are%20at%20a%20slightly%20greater%20risk%20than%20men', '_blank', 'noopener'); return false;\" data-uw-rm-brl=\"PR\" data-uw-original-href=\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8934078/#ref3:~:text=women%20are%20at%20a%20slightly%20greater%20risk%20than%20men\">more common in women than in men</a>. </p>"
          }
